<subsection xml:id="r-01-19" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

<title>Subscript Notation</title>

{


<p>
We usually use parentheses to indicate a function, as we see in the examples below:
	<me> f(x) = x^2 + 3x + 2, \mbox{ or } g(x) = x^5 \sin(x). </me>
Recall that we can use that rule on things other than just <m>x.</m>  For example,
	<md>
		<mrow>f(7)	\amp= 7^2 + 3\cdot 7 + 2 = 72</mrow>
		<mrow>\amp			</mrow>
		<mrow>f(-1.3)	\amp= (-1.3)^2 + 3 \cdot (-1.3) + 2 = -0.21</mrow>
		<mrow>\amp</mrow>
		<mrow>f(w)	\amp= w^2 + 3w + 2</mrow>
		<mrow>\amp</mrow>
		<mrow>f(x+5)	\amp= (x+5)^2 + 3(x+5) + 2</mrow>
		<mrow>\amp= x^2 + 10x + 25 + 3x + 15 + 2</mrow>
		<mrow>\amp= x^2 + 13x + 42</mrow>
	</md>
	
</p>

<p>
<em> Subscript notation</em> is just an alternate notation we use for functions when the input values
(i.e. the <em> domain</em>) consists of numbers like <m>n = 0, 1, 2, 3, \ldots</m>  Here's an example of subscript
notation:
	\begin{quote}
	<em> Example:</em>  Suppose <m>a_n = n^2 + 3n + 2.</m>
	
	
	<p>
    If you prefer to see a video of this example, 
    <xref ref="video-subscript_notation_01" text="custom"> click here </xref>
    </p>
    	
	Notice that this is much like the function <m>f(x),</m> except we would never evaluate this function at <m>-1.3</m>
	(because -1.3 is negative and is not an integer).
	
	We can evaluate this function at any nonnegative integer, though, as below:
	<md>
		<mrow>a_0	\amp= 0^2 + 3\cdot 0 + 2 = 2</mrow>
		<mrow>\amp</mrow>
		<mrow>a_1	\amp= 1^2 + 3\cdot 1 + 2 = 6</mrow>
		<mrow>\amp</mrow>
		<mrow>a_{13}	\amp= 13^2 + 3\cdot 13 + 2 = 210</mrow>
		<mrow>\amp</mrow>
		<mrow>a_{200}	\amp= 200^2 + 3\cdot 200 + 2 = 40602</mrow>
	</md>
	\end{quote}
</p>

<p>
Now you try: }
</p>

<p>
<em> Given the definition of a function in subscript notation, find the value of the given term.</em>
<ol>
	
		<li>
  If <m>a_n = 2n-5,</m> evaluate <m>a_4.</m>		
	<solution>		
		<me> a_4 = 2(4) - 5 = 3 </me>
		
	</solution>
	<answer>
		<me> a_4 = 3 </me>
		 
	</answer>
	
	
	
		</li>
	
		<li>
  If <m>x_n = -12,</m> evaluate <m>x_{41}.</m>		
	<solution>		
		<me> x_{41} = -12 </me>
		
	</solution>
	<answer>
		<me> x_{41} = -12 </me>
		 
	</answer>
	
	
	
		</li>
	
		<li>
  If <m>y_n = (n+1)!,</m> evaluate <m>y_3.</m>		
	<solution>		
		<me> y_{3} = (3+1)! = 4! = 24 </me>
		
	</solution>
	<answer>
		<me> y_{3} = 24 </me>
		 
	</answer>
	
	</li>
</ol>
</p>
</subsection>